\is1 Study Notes
\ili1 1. See of what importance it is that the Christian should always grow in the knowledge of sin. The sin that I do not know, I cannot bring to Jesus. The sin that I do not bring to Him is not taken out of me.
\ili1 2. To know sin better the following things are required:
\ili2 • The constant prayer, “Examine me; make known to me my transgression and my sin” \rq (Job 13:23; Psalm 139:23–24)\rq*.
\ili2 • A tender conscience that is willing to be convinced of sins through the Spirit, as He also uses the conscience for this end.
\ili2 • The very humble surrender to the Word, to think about sin only as God thinks.
\ili1 3. The deeper knowledge of sin will be found in these results:
\ili2 • That we will see as sin things which we previously did not regard in this light.
\ili2 • That we will more exceedingly perceive the detestable character of sin \rq (Romans 7:13)\rq*.
\ili2 • That with the overcoming of external sins we come to understand more clearly the deep sinfulness of our nature, of the enmity of our flesh against God. Then we give up all hope of being or of doing anything good, and we are turned wholly to live in faith through the Spirit.
\ili1 4. Let us thank God very heartily that Jesus is a Saviour from sin. The power that sin has had over us, Jesus now has. The place that sin has taken in the heart, Jesus will now take. “The law of the Spirit of life in Christ Jesus hath made me free from the law of sin and death” \rq (Romans 8:2)\rq*.
